00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:23.320
Recording by Jen Broda Peter Rabbit and Other Tales by Beatrix

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:27.760
Potter, The Tale of Benjamin Bunny

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:31.000
Good morning a little rabbit sat on a bank.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:36.160
He pricked his ears and listened to the trick-trot, trick-trot of a pony.

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:38.800
A gig was coming along the road.

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:45.160
It was driven by Mr. McGregor and beside him sat Mrs. McGregor in her best bonnet.

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:50.640
As soon as they had passed, Little Benjamin Bunny slid down into the road and set off with

00:00:50.640 --> 00:00:56.440
a hop skip and a jump to call upon his relations, who lived in the wood at the back of

00:00:56.440 --> 00:00:58.880
Mr. McGregor's garden.

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:04.440
The wood was full of rabbit holes, and in the neatest, sandiest hole of all, lived

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:11.040
Benjamin's aunt and his cousins, flopsie, mopsie, cottontail, and Peter.

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:12.920
Old Mrs. Rabbit was a widow.

00:01:12.920 --> 00:01:17.520
She earned her living by knitting rabbit wool mittens and muffetes.

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:20.240
I once bought a pair at a bizarre.

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:28.320
She also sold herbs and rosemary tea and rabbit tobacco, which is what we call lavender.

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:32.080
Little Benjamin did not very much want to see his aunt.

00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:38.240
He came round the back of the fur tree and nearly tumbled upon the top of his cousin Peter.

00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:40.200
Peter was sitting by himself.

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:45.360
He looked poorly and was dressed in a red cotton pocket hankerchief.

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:49.080
Peter said Little Benjamin in a whisper.

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:51.480
Who has got your clothes?

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:56.800
Peter replied, "The scare crawl in Mr. McGregor's garden."

00:01:56.800 --> 00:02:02.600
And described how he had been chased about the garden and had dropped his shoes and coat.

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:07.360
Little Benjamin sat down beside his cousin and assured him that Mr. McGregor had gone out

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:13.600
in a gig and Mrs. McGregor also, and certainly for the day because she was wearing her

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:15.800
best bonnet.

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:18.600
Peter said he hoped that it would rain.

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:23.720
At this point old Mrs. Rabbit's voice was heard inside the rabbit hole calling.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:28.360
Cotton tail, cotton tail, fetch some more chamomile.

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:32.440
Peter said he thought he might feel better if he went for a walk.

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:37.360
They went away hand in hand and got upon the flat top of the wall at the bottom of the

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:38.800
wood.

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:42.560
From here they looked down into Mr. McGregor's garden.

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:47.880
Peter's coat and shoes were plainly to be seen upon the scarecrow, topped with an old

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:51.600
Tamilchanter of Mr. McGregor's.

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:56.640
Little Benjamin said, "It spoils people's clothes to squeeze under a gate.

00:02:56.640 --> 00:03:01.840
The proper way to get in is to climb down a pear tree."

00:03:01.840 --> 00:03:07.960
Peter fell down head first, but it was of no consequence as the bed below was newly raked

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:09.880
and quite soft.

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:13.320
It had been sewn with lettuces.

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:18.880
They left a great many odd little footmarks all over the bed, especially a little Benjamin

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:21.520
who was wearing clogs.

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:26.280
Little Benjamin said that the first thing to be done was to get back Peter's clothes

00:03:26.280 --> 00:03:30.840
in order that they might be able to use the pocket hankerchief.

00:03:30.840 --> 00:03:33.000
They took them off the scarecrow.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.040
There had been rain during the night.

00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:39.320
There was water in the shoes and the coat was somewhat shrunk.

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:43.960
Then tried on the Tamilchanter, but it was too big for him.

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:48.480
Then he suggested that they should fill the pocket hankerchief with onions as a little

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:50.880
present for his aunt.

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:53.760
Peter did not seem to be enjoying himself.

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:56.080
He kept hearing noises.

00:03:56.080 --> 00:04:01.800
Benjamin, on the contrary, was perfectly at home and ate a lettuce leaf.

00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:06.040
He said that he was in the habit of coming to the garden with his father to get lettuces

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:08.160
for their Sunday dinner.

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:13.280
The name of little Benjamin's papa was old Mr. Benjamin bunny.

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:16.720
The lettuces certainly were very fine.

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:18.720
Peter did not eat anything.

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:21.160
He said he should like to go home.

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:24.800
Presently he dropped half the onions.

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:29.080
Little Benjamin said that it was not possible to get back up the pear tree with a load

00:04:29.080 --> 00:04:30.680
of vegetables.

00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:34.520
He led the way boldly towards the other end of the garden.

00:04:34.520 --> 00:04:39.680
They went along a little walk on planks under a sunny, red brick wall.

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:43.480
The mice sat on their doorstep, cracking cherry stones.

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:47.160
They winked at Peter Rabbit and little Benjamin bunny.

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:51.840
Presently, Peter Rabbit let the pocket hankerchief go again.

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:55.760
They got amongst flower pots and frames and tubs.

00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:58.120
Peter heard noises worse than ever.

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:01.160
His eyes were as big as lollipops.

00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:05.880
He was a stopper to in front of his cousin when he suddenly stopped.

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:09.840
This is what those little rabbits saw around the corner.

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:15.960
Little Benjamin took one look and then, in half a minute less than no time, he hid himself

00:05:15.960 --> 00:05:20.320
and Peter and the onions underneath a large basket.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:25.080
The cat got up and stretched herself and came and sniffed at the basket.

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:27.720
Perhaps she liked the smell of onions.

00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:32.160
Anyway, she sat down on top of the basket.

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:36.040
She sat there for five hours.

00:05:36.040 --> 00:05:40.480
I cannot draw you a picture of Peter and Benjamin underneath the basket because it was

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:46.400
quite dark and because the smell of onions was fearful, he'd made Peter Rabbit and

00:05:46.400 --> 00:05:48.680
little Benjamin cry.

00:05:48.680 --> 00:05:54.520
The sun got round behind the wood and it was quite late in the afternoon, but still the

00:05:54.520 --> 00:05:57.680
cat sat upon the basket.

00:05:57.680 --> 00:06:02.880
At length there was a pitter patter, pitter patter, and some bits of mortar fell from the

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:04.520
wall above.

00:06:04.520 --> 00:06:10.240
The cat looked up and saw old Mr. Benjamin bunny, prancing along the top of the wall of the

00:06:10.240 --> 00:06:11.880
upper terrace.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:17.320
He was smoking a pipe of Rabbit tobacco and had a little switch in his hand.

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:20.160
He was looking for his son.

00:06:20.160 --> 00:06:23.840
Old Mr. Bunny had no opinion whatever of cats.

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:29.160
He took a tremendous jump off the top of the wall onto the top of the cat and cuffed

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:35.720
it off the basket and kicked it into the greenhouse, scratching off a handful of fur.

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:39.400
The cat was too surprised to scratch back.

00:06:39.400 --> 00:06:44.480
When old Mr. Bunny had driven the cat into the greenhouse, he locked the door.

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:49.280
Then he came back to the basket and took out his son Benjamin by the ears and whipped him

00:06:49.280 --> 00:06:51.400
with the little switch.

00:06:51.400 --> 00:06:54.160
Then he took out his nephew pitter.

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:59.200
Then he took out the hankerchief of onions and marched out of the garden.

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:04.080
When Mr. McGregor returned about half an hour later, he observed several things which

00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:05.840
perplexed him.

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:11.160
It looked as though some person had been walking all over the garden in a pair of clogs.

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:14.880
Only the footmarks were too ridiculously little.

00:07:14.880 --> 00:07:20.440
Also he could not understand how the cat could have managed to shut herself up inside

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:25.280
the greenhouse, locking the door upon the outside.

00:07:25.280 --> 00:07:30.320
When Peter got home, his mother forgave him because she was so glad to see that he had

00:07:30.320 --> 00:07:32.920
found his shoes and coat.

00:07:32.920 --> 00:07:38.120
Cottontail and Peter folded up the pocket hankerchief and old Mrs. Rabbit strung up the

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:43.400
onions and hung them from the kitchen ceiling with the bunches of herbs and the rabbit

00:07:43.400 --> 00:07:45.200
tobacco.

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:50.600
The end of the tail of Benjamin Bunny.
